Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Fill and boil the #kettle{} with water to use for the
@quinoa{120%g}. Pop the @diced butternut squash{300%g} onto a lined #baking tray{}.
Sprinkle over half the @Mexican style spice mix{1/2} and season with @salt{} and
@black pepper{}. Drizzle on a little oil then rub the seasoning all over the squash
to evenly coat. Arrange in one layer, then pop on the top shelf of your oven.
Roast until tender and golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

Meanwhile, pour some water into a large #saucepan{} and bring back to the boil.
Pop the quinoa and half the @vegetable stock powder{1/2} into the pan. Stir to
dissolve the stock powder, then reduce the heat. Simmer until the quinoa has
doubled in size and the seed has visibly split, ~{12-15%minutes}. Once cooked,
drain in a #sieve{} and return to the pan, off the heat. Cover with a #lid{} and
set aside.

Drain and rinse the @black beans{1%400g can} in the sieve. Pop the
@water{100%ml}(for the beans) into a small saucepan over a high heat. Stir in the
remaining @vegetable stock powder{1/2} and Mexican spice and the @ground cumin{2%tsp}.
Add the black beans then use a #potato masher{} (or fork) to mash up about half
of the beans. Bring the water to the boil then reduce the heat slightly. Simmer
rapidly for ~{10-15%minutes}, stirring often, until the water has evaporated and
you are left with a thick bean purée.

While everything is cooking, roughly chop the @coriander{1} (stalks and all). Zest
and halve the @lime{1}. Trim the @spring onion{1} then slice thinly. Chop the
@tomato{2%medium} into small chunks and pop into a small #bowl{}. Add the lime
zest, juice from half the lime, a pinch of @salt{} and a good grind of @black
pepper{}.

Once your beans are done (you may want to add a splash more water if they appear
too dry), mix in half the coriander and some lime juice to taste. Once the
quinoa is done, stir in the remaining coriander, half the spring onion and
season with salt and pepper to taste.

Divide the quinoa between your bowls. Cover one third with the Mexican style
beans, one third with the tomato salad and the final third with the
@wild rocket{40%g}. Pop the roasted squash on top and sprinkle over the
@pumpkin seeds{15%g} and remaining spring onion. Enjoy!

> Quinoa is a pseudo-cereal and is one of a few plant foods which can be considered
> to be a complete protein as it contains all 9 essential amino acids. Hearty and
> wholesome, this healthy recipe is perfect for an easy mid-week dinner.